<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="53">
[[ Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0D770073-F927-4B83-AB82-EB1197B34FB6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Brachionichthys Bleeker 1855:12, 21" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Brachionichthys Bleeker</taxonomicName>
]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="53">
Members of the Australian endemic fish family Brachionichthyidae, or handfishes, are considered to be the most primitive group of the lophiiform suborder Antennarioidei (Pietsch, 1981; Pietsch &amp; Grobecker, 1987). The group presently consists of two extant genera, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0D770073-F927-4B83-AB82-EB1197B34FB6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Brachionichthys Bleeker 1855:12, 21" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Brachionichthys Bleeker, 1855</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:12960337-D0BC-4BF5-8C79-BF890F51EA3A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Sympterichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sympterichthys Gill 1878:222" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sympterichthys Gill, 1878</taxonomicName>
, and 4 valid nominal taxa, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
B. hirsutus (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lacepède">Lacepede</normalizedToken>
, 1804)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Sympterichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="politus">S. politus (Richardson, 1844)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Sympterichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unipennis">S. unipennis (Cuvier, 1817)</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:245BB024-AE00-4533-B7EF-D859256243CA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Sympterichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sympterichthys verrucosus McCulloch &amp; Waite 1918:76" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="verrucosus">S. verrucosus McCulloch &amp; Waite, 1918</taxonomicName>
(Paxton et al., 2006). However, recent studies by the authors, have found that the family contains at least 8 undescribed species and additional genus-level taxa. Three of these new species were discovered during the preparation of a monograph on Tasmanian fishes (Last et al., 1983) and two of them were discussed in a guide to the coastal fishes of Tasmania and Bass Strait (Edgar et al., 1982).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="53">
Handfishes were amongst the first Australian fishes named (Last &amp; Bruce, 1997). The French zoologist 
<normalizedToken originalValue="François">Francois</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Péron">Peron</normalizedToken>
collected 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirsutus">B. hirsutus</taxonomicName>
from Tasmania (then known as Van Diemens Land) in the early 19th century on the Baudin expedition (1800-04), and these were subsequently described by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lacepède">Lacepede</normalizedToken>
and Cuvier.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
Their subsequent appearance in scant regional literature suggests that they were reasonably common off southeastern Tasmania during the 19th century. More recently, populations of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirsutus">B. hirsutus</taxonomicName>
have become severely depleted and the species is now considered to be critically endangered by the IUCN (2006), or endangered by the State Government of Tasmania (Department of Primary Industries and Water, State Government of Tasmania, 2007) and the Federal Government of Australia (Department of the Environment and Water Resources, 2007).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
In this paper, the new handfish, discussed and figured as 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sp. 2">Brachionichthys sp. 2</taxonomicName>
in Last et al, (1983), is formally described. 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Brachionichthyidae" genus="Brachionichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirsutus">Brachionichthys hirsutus</taxonomicName>
, described briefly and simply by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lacepède">Lacepede</normalizedToken>
(1804) as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F261DF15-33BF-45BE-A020-5ACDF823FAC9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lophiidae" genus="Lophius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Lophius hirsutus Lacépède 1804:202, 210" order="Lophiiformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hirsutus">Lophius hirsutus</taxonomicName>
, is redescribed based on recent material.
</paragraph>
